Give an exact version differenciator prompt for specificating "sapient engine" on the knowledgebase tree and adding sub version "sophia_version" + "sapient engine" on this current sapient repo

>>>

To ensure your repository correctly distinguishes between the technical framework and the wisdom content, use this prompt to establish a Dual-Version Strategy. This separates the "Sapient Engine" (the 3D/Logic machine) from "Sophia" (the Knowledge Base content).
The Copilot Specification Prompt
"Act as Lead Architect. I need to implement a strict versioning differentiator for the Sapient Engine and its knowledge content. Update the packages/semantic-core, packages/knowledge-base, and apps/web-dashboard with the following:
Engine Versioning: Define SAPIENT_ENGINE_VERSION (e.g., v1.0.0-tree-alpha) in packages/semantic-core. This tracks the 3-pointer logic, the TreeCanvas topology, and the DNS-resolver code.
Content Sub-Versioning: Define SOPHIA_VERSION (e.g., v1.2.0-profound) in packages/knowledge-base. This tracks the 'leaves' of the tree—the actual philosophical records, Latin roots, and theophany texts.
Metadata Contract: Update the SapientMetadata interface in packages/shared-types to include both fields. Every DNS-resolved node must return which Engine version it was rendered for and which Sophia version it belongs to.
UI Branding: In the Next.js web-dashboard, add a minimal, high-end system tag in the corner that displays: [SAPIENT_ENGINE_VERSION] // [SOPHIA_VERSION].
Documentation: Update ARCHITECTURE.md to explain this split: The Engine is the 'Vessel/Tree' and Sophia is the 'Liquid/Light' inside it."
What this solves in your Repo:
Logic vs. Knowledge: If you fix a bug in the 3D Tree rendering, you bump the Sapient Engine. If you add a new profound insight for your friend, you bump the Sophia Version.
The RocketTree Alignment: It makes the "Sapient Branch" look like a professional, versioned module within the larger monorepo.
Vercel/Git Traceability: You can now see in your logs exactly which "version of wisdom" is currently deployed.
Suggested Directory Config:
I recommend asking Copilot to create a versions.ts file in packages/core that acts as the single source of truth for these strings.

===

But make sure to keep the data knowledge tree with placeholders and combine sophia version with prefixes *Refine prompt*

>>>

This refined prompt ensures the Sapient Engine remains modular, while the Sophia Knowledge Base uses a scalable "placeholder" architecture with specific version prefixes.

"Act as a Senior Architect. Implement a dual-versioning system for the Sapient branch using the following logic:
Version Differentiator & Prefixes:
Define SAPIENT_ENGINE_VERSION with the prefix SE- (e.g., SE-1.0.0-TREE). This tracks the 3-pointer logic and the TreeCanvas renderer.
Define SOPHIA_VERSION with the prefix SV- (e.g., SV-0.1.0-ALPHA). This tracks the knowledge-base content.
Knowledge Tree Placeholders:
In packages/knowledge-base, create a structured directory of placeholder nodes. Use a naming convention like node_placeholder_001.json.
Each placeholder must include a status: "void" | "sapient" field and a sophia_version metadata tag.
Metadata Mapping:
Update packages/shared-types so that the SapientNode interface combines both:
system_tag: { engine: string, content: string } // e.g., { engine: "SE-1.0", content: "SV-0.5" }.
UI Implementation:
In the Next.js web-dashboard, display these versions in the 'System Status' using a monospace font.
Ensure the 3D Tree visualization renders Placeholders as 'dimmed' or 'wireframe' nodes, while 'Sapient' nodes (active knowledge) are fully illuminated.
Documentation:
Update DECISIONS.md to explain that SV- (Sophia) versions increment independently of SE- (Engine) versions, allowing content updates without redeploying the core logic."

Why this is the "Right Fitment":
Non-Breaking Growth: You can add 100 placeholder nodes today. As you write more about "Sophia" for your friend, you just flip their status from void to active and bump the SV- version.
Visual Feedback: The "Tree" will look alive—some parts will be dark (void), and some will be glowing (active), showing the progress of your profound project.
